    </section>

    <!-- Why Stress Triggers Food Urges -->
    <section class="py-16 md:py-20 px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 bg-white">
      <div class="container mx-auto max-w-4xl">
        <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-6">
          Why Stress Triggers Food Urges
        </h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-neutral-600 mb-8 leading-relaxed">
          The connection between stress and eating isn't weakness — it's biology and psychology working together:
        </p>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
          <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-2xl p-6 hover:shadow-md transition-shadow">
            <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-primary-100 rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center mb-4">
              <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-primary-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9.663 17h4.673M12 3v1m6.364 1.636l-.707.707M21 12h-1M4 12H3m3.343-5.657l-.707-.707m2.828 9.9a5 5 0 117.072 0l-.548.547A3.374 3.374 0 0014 18.469V19a2 2 0 11-4 0v-.531c0-.895-.356-1.754-.988-2.386l-.548-.547z"></path>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-2">The Cortisol Connection</h3>
            <p class="text-neutral-600">When you're stressed, your body releases cortisol — the "stress hormone." Elevated cortisol increases appetite and specifically drives cravings for high-fat, high-sugar foods. This isn't weakness; it's biology.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-2xl p-6 hover:shadow-md transition-shadow">
            <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-secondary-100 rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center mb-4">
