                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M14.828 14.828a4 4 0 01-5.656 0M9 10h.01M15 10h.01M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"></path>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-2">The Dopamine Response</h3>
            <p class="text-neutral-600">Eating certain foods triggers dopamine release in your brain's reward center. When stress depletes your emotional resources, food becomes a quick way to feel better — even if the relief is temporary.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-2xl p-6 hover:shadow-md transition-shadow">
            <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-accent-100 rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center mb-4">
              <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-accent-400" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M4.318 6.318a4.5 4.5 0 000 6.364L12 20.364l7.682-7.682a4.5 4.5 0 00-6.364-6.364L12 7.636l-1.318-1.318a4.5 4.5 0 00-6.364 0z"></path>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-2">Emotional Regulation</h3>
            <p class="text-neutral-600">For many people, food becomes a way to manage emotions they don't know how to process otherwise. Stress creates tension, and eating provides temporary relief from that uncomfortable feeling.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-2xl p-6 hover:shadow-md transition-shadow">
            <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-primary-100 rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center mb-4">
              <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-primary-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M4 4v5h.582m15.356 2A8.001 8.001 0 004.582 9m0 0H9m11 11v-5h-.581m0 0a8.003 8.003 0 01-15.357-2m15.357 2H15"></path>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-2">Learned Behavior</h3>
            <p class="text-neutral-600">If you were comforted with food as a child, or learned to associate eating with stress relief, these patterns become automatic. Stress triggers the behavior without conscious thought.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-2xl p-6 hover:shadow-md transition-shadow md:col-span-2">
            <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-secondary-100 rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center mb-4">
              <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-secondary-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13.875 18.825A10.05 10.05 0 0112 19c-4.478 0-8.268-2.943-9.543-7a9.97 9.97 0 011.563-3.029m5.858.908a3 3 0 114.243 4.243M9.878 9.878l4.242 4.242M9.88 9.88l-3.29-3.29m7.532 7.532l3.29 3.29M3 3l3.59 3.59m0 0A9.953 9.953 0 0112 5c4.478 0 8.268 2.943 9.543 7a10.025 10.025 0 01-4.132 5.411m0 0L21 21"></path>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-2">Avoidance Mechanism</h3>
            <p class="text-neutral-600">Sometimes eating when stressed isn't about the food at all — it's about avoiding the stressor. Food provides a distraction, a delay, a way to not deal with what's actually bothering you.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
